","end_year":1836,"children_ids":["H01494","H01495","H01496","H01497","H01498","H01499","H01500","H01501","H01502","H01503"]}],"education":[],"career":[],"military_service":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"naming_inspiration":[{"name_element":"Selah","inspired_by_id":"H00273","description":"Named for his uncle Gen. Selah Hart of Kensington — the same uncle who later adopted his orphaned brother Cyprian (H00562) in 1773 and raised him at the General Hart homestead."}],"artworks":[],"tags":["ohio_migration","unusual_death"],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"migration","header":"Settled at Marietta on the Ohio frontier","body":"Fifth son of Nathaniel Hart No. 2, named for his uncle General Selah Hart of Kensington who had adopted his brother Cyprian. Migrated from Connecticut to the Ohio frontier — among the early settlers at Marietta, Washington County, in the Ohio Company's territory. EH #561 records his Ohio descendants at numbers 1494-1503."},{"number":2,"category":"death","header":"Killed by a falling tree in Ohio, 1836","body":"He died in Ohio in 1836, killed by a falling tree. One son Norman had been killed earlier at Sandusky in 1813 during the War of 1812. EH numbers ten Ohio-born descendants in the next generation."},{"number":3,"category":"career","header":"Fourteen years a magistrate of excellent judgment","body":"He served as a magistrate at Marion, Morgan County, Ohio for about fourteen years, and was generally accounted of good judgment and local influence. Both he and his wife Sarah were active church members from early life. The Hart Genealogy of 1875 records that the place was greatly missed and mourned over at his death, so great was the loss."}],"quotes":[],"sources":[{"short":"Andrews, Genealogical History of Deacon Stephen Hart (1875)","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/2/25/Geneological_history_of_Deacon_Stephen_Hart_and_his_descendants%2C_1632._1875%2C_%28IA_geneologicalh